{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476724"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:51:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:51:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13940"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13940"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.07,0.04,0.16,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6566"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107267"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6566"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13940"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89727"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"302"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1359"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12910"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13246"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44185"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44718"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107267"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of fever and lethargy. His parents report the appearance of a rash over the last few hours. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with his immunisations. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with mottled, cold peripheries and a purpuric rash. His pulse rate is 180/min, blood pressure 75/40 mmHg, respiratory rate 40/min with grunting respirations, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 39.5\u00b0C. High-flow oxygen via non-rebreathing mask is commenced. Two attempts at establishing peripheral intravenous access are unsuccessful, and a fluid bolus is urgently required.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Central venous line placement via femoral approach","External jugular vein cannulation under ultrasound guidance","Saphenous vein cutdown at the ankle","Administration of paracetamol, nasogastric fluids, intramuscular ceftriaxone and reattempt intravenous access in 10 minutes","Insertion of intraosseous needle"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with features suggestive of septic shock, likely due to meningococcal septicaemia given the purpuric rash. In this critically ill child requiring urgent fluid resuscitation, the most appropriate next step is \u003Cstrong\u003Einsertion of an intraosseous needle\u003C/strong\u003E. Intraosseous access is the recommended route for rapid vascular access in critically ill children when intravenous access cannot be obtained quickly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral venous line placement via femoral approach\u003C/strong\u003E is a more time-consuming procedure that requires a higher level of skill and is not recommended as a first-line option in this emergency situation. It may be considered if intraosseous access fails or is contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal jugular vein cannulation under ultrasound guidance\u003C/strong\u003E can be challenging in a young child, especially one who is unwell and potentially uncooperative. It is not the preferred option when easier and quicker alternatives like intraosseous access are available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESaphenous vein cutdown at the ankle\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical procedure that requires more time and expertise than intraosseous access. While it can provide reliable vascular access, it is not the first-line approach in emergency situations where rapid access is needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadminister paracetamol, nasogastric fluids, intramuscular ceftriaxone and reattempt intravenous access in 10 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate in this critically ill child. Delaying fluid resuscitation and appropriate antibiotic therapy could lead to further deterioration. While antibiotics are crucial, they should ideally be given intravenously, which requires immediate vascular access.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn paediatric septic shock, early recognition and aggressive management are crucial to improve outcomes. This includes rapid fluid resuscitation and early antibiotic administration, which necessitates immediate vascular access. Intraosseous access provides a quick and reliable route for both these interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intraosseous access is the preferred route for rapid vascular access in critically ill children when intravenous access cannot be obtained.","Early recognition and aggressive management of paediatric sepsis is crucial to improve outcomes.","Purpuric rash with fever and shock in a child should raise suspicion for meningococcal septicaemia."],"references":["Perth Children\u2019s Hospital. Sepsis recognition and management [Internet]. Perth Children\u0027s Hospital; [cited 2024 Jul 15]. Available from: https://pch.health.wa.gov.au/For-health-professionals/Emergency-Department-Guidelines/Sepsis-recognition-and-management"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89727"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13940"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89727"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-27T10:32:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-27T10:34:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6566"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107267"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api